Each line can be divided into $2\times 3 = 6$ groups of 3 points, one for each of the vertical or horizontal segments of the line. So there are $3\times 6 = 18$ sets of points lying on each line.

There are $4$ vertical lines and $4$ horizontal lines, for a total of $4 + 4 = 8$ lines. Each of the $3$ lines is covered by $18$ sets, and $8$ sets were actually chosen, so by the principle of inclusion-exclusion we have $\frac{18\times 8}{3^{3}}=\frac{144}{27}=\boxed{\frac{32}{9}}$.

Alternatively, one can simply realize that there are 18 ways of choosing one point, then 16 ways of choosing the second point, and then 12 ways of choosing the third point, for a total of $18 \times 16 \times 12 = 3456.$ Now, to account for ordering, we must divide by 6, since we are counting all 6 points on the line to be included in the set 3 times. Now, since we are choosing 3 points from 3 points, this is equal to $\frac{3456}{6\times 3}=\frac{3456}{18}=186\dfrac{12}{18}=102+\frac{6}{18}=102+\frac{1}{3}=\boxed{\frac{32}{9}}.$รัง
